The grip is the rubber Hogue grip and the folding bipod is of heavy duty steel. The rifle shoots great and has been well cared for. I got the rifle used so I do not know how many rounds have been shot through it. Examples of these rifles without the accessories are going for around $1900-$2000, do the math and you see that the listed price is well worth it. title: For Sale:  NOVESKE AFGHAN 14.5(PINNED)MATCHGRADE COMBAT RIFLE         COMPLETE AR-15 SET-UP HIGHEST QUALITY PARTS USED
postcontent: This is a complete custom built noveske afghan 5.56 14.5 pinned and welded (for legal compliance). this rifle was purpose built to be the most accurate combat rifle money can buy. all parts are top of the line.everything on this gun is brand new and has not been fired. the barrel of course was test fired at the noveske factory. i had 3 6.8 pro mags and threw them in the auction also figuring whoever buys this gun knows there stuff and can use the mags or knows someone that can. EXPLANATION OF CHOSEN PARTS: starting from the back to the front of the gun. i chose the CTR stock because it is a battle proven weapon and has a lock on it to prevent it from wiggling, on the ctr stock is a LaRue RISR and LaRue POD (read below for abbreviation meaning). the RISR helps aid in accuracy by putting the face in a higher height of position perfectly aligning it with your sights, it also is retractible meaning when you pull back the charging handle the RISR moves back and snaps back into its original position keeping your charging motions fluent instead of backing off the stock and backing it forward to charge your gun like all other cheek risers. the LaRue POD was picked for when shooting in prone position, you can let the back of the gun rest evenly on the ground to enhance accuracy. the enhance magpul butt-pad also reduces recoil enhance accuracy yet again. inside the BCM buffer tube is a blue springco spring and spikes tactical st-t2 heavy buffer, after some research the st-t2 buffer would be perfect fitting for the 14.5 noveske barrel, i chose springco springs because they are the best and most likely last over 10,000 rounds with no fatigue, but I'm excessive and bought 4 one for the gun and 3 extra (2 blue, 2 white). noveske QD endplate to go with the tactical link sling. magpul MOE+ grip cause it it rubberized for better grip, lightweight, and has storage capacity. Bad-Ass selector switch for its durability and styling. yankee hill machine pivot pins for quick easy access to the internals. geissele super dynamic combat trigger cause its accuracy is crisp and superb for a combat effective weapon. holding the geissele trigger in place is some ins ten 2 anti rotational pins obviously to prevent the trigger pins from walking out. a wmd nickel-boron full auto bolt carrier group for its easy cleaning, self lubricating, and smooth action. rainier arms raptor charging handle for it ambidextrous properties. seekins precision bolt catch and mag release for their textured grip and styling, and norgon ambi-catch mag release on opposite side. as you can see i tried to put as many ambidextrous parts on the gun as i could for that possible moment your primary arm is injured and unusable. pmags were chosen mail for there lightweight but the durability of them is uncompromising. the reason i chose the seekins precision SAR 12" rail over the noveske NSR is plainly because the NSR can not take tough abuse and needs key mod picatinny mounts for items(lights,grips,lasers,etc..), attachments can be put wherever whenever on the SAR without having to unscrew any key mod attachments. noveske barrel for accuracy in shorter barrels, 14.5 because its the perfect size for the guns intentions. rainier arms low profile match grade gas block for its match grade qualities and its .005 larger for better fitment on match grade barrels. the AAC blackout 51t flash hider (pinned and welded) was chosen for toughness and suppressor ready capability which i thought was perfect cause it can't be removed anyway, giving you the option to add a suppressor in the future if you wish to do so. finally the pelican case simply cause they're the best, i also left the top area of the foam uncut for when iron sights or/and a scope is added

location: HIGH POINT-GREENSBORO-WINSTON, North Carolina, United States
postcontent:
Remington Model 788 Caliber .222 Remington Early 1970's
Weaver K4 C3 4 X 38 Scope Fine Cross Hairs Blued Steel Tube + Mounts
3 & 1/2 Boxes (71 Rds.) .222 Rem 50 Grain SP
Rifle Case $620.00 OBO

The Remington 788 is an accurate hunting rifle developed by the Remington Arms Company.

The 788 utilizes a single-column detachable magazine holding 4 rounds. A .22 rimfire model was also produced known as the 580, 581, or 582 depending on its method of feed.

A target version was used by the US military[2] as a training rifle and later disposed through the Civilian Marksmanship Program.

Distinguishing design characteristics
The Remington 788 has two distinguishing design features. The first is the rear-lugged bolt. The bolt has nine lugs in three rows of three lugs each. They lock into the receiver behind the magazine well. Due to this design, the bolt handle lifts only 60 degrees on opening giving more clearance for scopes compared to the 90 degrees required for the Model 700 and other two-lug rifles.
The bolt travel is also reduced because of the rear lugs. The locking bolt requires the safety to be in the "fire" or "off" position in order to rotate the handle and actuate the bolt. Rifles manufactured from 1975 to 1983 have non-locking bolts which can be actuated while the safety is engaged.
The second distinguishing feature is the receiver. It has a smaller ejection port than similar bolt action rifles, and no bolt lug raceways. The single stack magazine design yields a smaller feed opening in the bottom of the receiver compared to rifles using a double stack magazine well.
When machining of these smaller ports is complete there is more steel remaining in the receiver between the ejection port and adjacent feed port, and significantly more steel overall where all receivers have the least strength.
These characteristics combined to make the Remington 788 receiver more rigid and stronger than most, if not all, competing designs, including the Remington 700 which shares the same outside receiver diameter.
A rifle's accuracy tends to increase slightly as the rigidity of the receiver increases, as this slightly reduces barrel deflection during firing. Thus the Remington 788 has the structural foundation to be a very accurate rifle.

title: For Sale:  Rem. Model 788 + Ammo+ Case
location: HIGH POINT-GREENSBORO-WINSTON, North Carolina, United States
postcontent:
Remington Model 788 Caliber .222 Remington Early 1970's
Weaver K4 C3 4 X 38 Scope Fine Cross Hairs Blued Steel Tube + Mounts
3 & 1/2 Boxes (71 Rds.) .222 Rem 50 Grain SP
Rifle Case 
$620.00--- OBO

The Remington 788 is an accurate hunting rifle developed by the Remington Arms Company.

The 788 utilizes a single-column detachable magazine holding 4 rounds. A .22 rimfire model was also produced known as the 580, 581, or 582 depending on its method of feed.

A target version was used by the US military[2] as a training rifle and later disposed through the Civilian Marksmanship Program.

Distinguishing design characteristics
The Remington 788 has two distinguishing design features. The first is the rear-lugged bolt. The bolt has nine lugs in three rows of three lugs each. They lock into the receiver behind the magazine well. Due to this design, the bolt handle lifts only 60 degrees on opening giving more clearance for scopes compared to the 90 degrees required for the Model 700 and other two-lug rifles.
The bolt travel is also reduced because of the rear lugs. The locking bolt requires the safety to be in the "fire" or "off" position in order to rotate the handle and actuate the bolt. Rifles manufactured from 1975 to 1983 have non-locking bolts which can be actuated while the safety is engaged.
The second distinguishing feature is the receiver. It has a smaller ejection port than similar bolt action rifles, and no bolt lug raceways. The single stack magazine design yields a smaller feed opening in the bottom of the receiver compared to rifles using a double stack magazine well.
When machining of these smaller ports is complete there is more steel remaining in the receiver between the ejection port and adjacent feed port, and significantly more steel overall where all receivers have the least strength.
These characteristics combined to make the Remington 788 receiver more rigid and stronger than most, if not all, competing designs, including the Remington 700 which shares the same outside receiver diameter.
A rifle's accuracy tends to increase slightly as the rigidity of the receiver increases, as this slightly reduces barrel deflection during firing. Thus the Remington 788 has the structural foundation to be a very accurate rifle.

title: For Sale:  AR Performance Barrels 16" 5.56 for AR-15 Builders
postcontent:
AR-15 BUILDERS, 16" BARREL:

5.56 AR Performance Barrel,  16 inches long and:

Is a mid weight at 2 pounds 2 ounces.  It has a heavier SOCOM profile similar to the military replacement of the M4 barrel.

Is made of 4150 11595-e alloy, milspec CMV, nitro-carburized (QPQ Melonite) treated barrels which have been shown to last much longer than chrome lined barrels. Melonite gives a very hard surface treatment allowing you to shoot steel cased ammo or any 5.56/.223 ammo.

Has a 1 in 8 twist ratio to handle all but the heaviest 90 grain bullets.

Uses hybrid 5R rifling which means 5 lands and 5 grooves instead of the traditional 6. The sides of each land are cut at a proprietary (hybrid) angle versus the usual 90 degrees. This results in less bullet jacket deformation and when the bullet jacket is less deformed there will be less jacket fouling in the grooves. You get tighter groups, greater bullet stability over multiple shots, and a rifle barrel that’s easier to clean.

Has a mid length gas system allowing more time for the pressure in the chamber to lower (the shell will have more time to contract), making extraction easier, which means less stress on the bolt, carrier and extractor.  The extractor may be the single most broken part; if the extractor breaks the rifle stops running. The mid length gas system also softens the recoil impulse felt by the operator.

Has a .223 wylde chamber; shoot .223 or 5.56 NATO including steel cased ammo.

All barrels have M4 feed ramps and use a .750 gas block.

NOTICE*** THIS BARREL HAS 5/8-24 threads to keep the bore at the muzzle from swelling like most barrels threaded 1/2-28. The tighter bore at the crown gives better accuracy. Do not use Armalite 308 crush washers, YHM or DPMS 5/8 or 308 crush washers work better.
